    "created_at": "2017-07-12T18:26:54Z",
    "updated_at": "2017-07-12T18:26:54Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I agree with your first point. A trustless crowdsale should encode all necessary actions (such as further minting) in the crowdsale finalization. In that case, I think anyone should be able to trigger it.\r\n\r\nA derived contract can always add extra requirements to an inherited function. A specific crowdsale would be able to restrict finalizing to an owner by subclassing Crowdsale and adding a check, if so desired.\r\n\r\nI'd like to reiterate two points though.\r\n1. Allowing anyone to trigger finalization enlarges the attack surface of the contract.\r\n2. Full trustlessness is impossible. We aim for trust minimization.\r\n\r\nWhatever path we choose it's important that it be very well communicated. I'll think about it a bit more. What would you guys think about providing the less restrictive option (anyone can finalize) by default?",
